But, yeah, I've been working on this project for a few months.

00:03:58.500 --> 00:04:00.180
We kind of kicked it off in May.

00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:04.980
The idea kind of floated around in May at the Build Conference,

00:04:05.270 --> 00:04:06.780
which is Microsoft's developer conference.

00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:12.140
After talking to a lot of different developers and people in Microsoft,

00:04:12.390 --> 00:04:16.840
we were kind of kicking around the idea of if we looked at this again.

00:04:18.400 --> 00:04:20.799
So like running Python code from.NET,

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:22.180
like how would you approach it?

00:04:23.500 --> 00:04:26.320
I kind of had some ideas, put some ideas together

00:04:26.520 --> 00:04:30.440
and then started working with Aaron on a really early prototype

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:33.780
just to see like if it was even possible.

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:36.740
And then we kind of got something working,

00:04:37.960 --> 00:04:39.680
chucked it in the bin, pretty much started again

00:04:41.420 --> 00:04:42.640
and then redesigned it.

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:46.480
And then, yeah, we've been sort of fiddling with it ever since.

00:04:51.380 --> 00:04:57.960
from my perspective i said before i am i'm not a python person but as someone in the.net

00:04:58.360 --> 00:05:05.900
ecosystem looking at the breadth of libraries that exist for python um like there's there's a lot

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:10.840
of things that you know i would have loved to have used particularly doing um some of the ai stuff

00:05:10.940 --> 00:05:13.260
that we've been doing in projects recently,

00:05:13.820 --> 00:05:17.300
there's just not as many packages or options in the.NET space.

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:18.920
So it's always been that like,

00:05:19.680 --> 00:05:21.860
okay, well, if I want to learn this,

00:05:21.940 --> 00:05:23.320
the tutorial is in Python

00:05:23.560 --> 00:05:26.000
or the package it recommends using is in Python.

00:05:26.060 --> 00:05:28.040
So it was always kind of like,

00:05:28.380 --> 00:05:30.880
how do we bridge that gap?

00:05:32.200 --> 00:05:36.039
And that was kind of one of the early thinkings

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:39.340
of just that's a clear problem space, right?

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:47.200
A lot of people are learning that, but then going into industry and maybe Python isn't the language that the organization they're working with is using.

00:05:47.210 --> 00:05:55.760
So how do we still have that fundamental knowledge that they've gained or the tooling they want to use available to us?

00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:03.720
Well, just think about me. I'm sure you have thought about how much of an explosion in possibility it is.

00:06:03.980 --> 00:06:20.900
If you can say, and by the way, there's almost 600,000 other libraries, including the biggest community of AI-based resources that are now, as far as you're concerned, native to.NET, right?

00:06:21.940 --> 00:06:22.060
Yeah.

00:06:22.580 --> 00:06:25.060
From the way you consume it, not the way it runs, is what I mean.

00:06:25.560 --> 00:06:26.120
Exactly, yeah.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:31.320
Like you mentioned there, nearly 600,000 Python packages.

00:06:31.330 --> 00:06:36.380
And you add that to, there's like 400,000 packages on NuGet for.NET.

00:06:36.780 --> 00:06:39.940
Like you got quite literally a million possibilities.

00:06:40.740 --> 00:06:41.040
Yeah.

00:06:41.550 --> 00:06:42.040
Yeah, it's amazing.

00:06:42.410 --> 00:06:45.680
And just for people listening, primarily Python audience,

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:49.360
NuGet is.NET's equivalent of our PyPI.

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:50.820
Yep.

00:06:52.560 --> 00:06:52.960
Yep, yep.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:54.140
Okay.

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:56.420
So Anthony, you had this idea.

00:06:56.600 --> 00:06:58.940
Somebody said, hey, how would you go about doing this?

00:07:00.740 --> 00:07:01.600
And then you were sucked in.

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:05.860
Yeah, it was actually one of the sort of lead

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:10.060
designers on.NET asked me at Build.

00:07:10.300 --> 00:07:15.520
They said, oh, we've been looking at how you might integrate Python

00:07:15.680 --> 00:07:16.600
into.NET for a while.

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:18.940
Like, if you were to approach it, how would you do it?

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:23.459
And I kind of went through all the projects that have tried this

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:29.880
in the past or there are different ways of doing it and pros and cons of each and kind

00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:33.300
of the pros and cons of a really low level integration and a high level one.

00:07:33.530 --> 00:07:39.600
So like a high level one would be stick a FastAPI on top of your Python app and just call

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:41.180
it via HTTP rest.

00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:46.180
Somehow auto generate some rest endpoints and then make those.

00:07:46.370 --> 00:07:52.080
And you could use it like an open API spec on top of it and auto generate a client and

00:07:52.090 --> 00:07:52.540
stuff like that.

00:07:52.660 --> 00:07:54.960
Like that's like the high level option.

00:07:56.200 --> 00:07:58.540
And then like the lowest level option is like,

00:07:59.120 --> 00:08:01.800
you know, you could get into the bytecode level,

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:04.340
which I've explored years ago with Pigeon.

00:08:06.380 --> 00:08:09.040
And yeah, that's a very deep, dark tunnel.

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:15.280
It's full of terrible edge cases and corners and sharp edges.

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:15.640
Yeah.

00:08:16.300 --> 00:08:18.020
And one of the challenges there is that the,

00:08:19.479 --> 00:08:23.960
like Python's implementation is changing so rapidly right now.

00:08:25.400 --> 00:08:30.300
Like, but just in Python 3.13 and looking at 3.14 now

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:31.860
and like all the changes and stuff in there,

00:08:31.960 --> 00:08:33.840
like it's just continuously changing.

00:08:34.200 --> 00:08:36.659
So it needs to be a happy medium

00:08:36.860 --> 00:08:40.060
in terms of how we blend the two together.

00:08:40.659 --> 00:08:44.560
So there has to be some level of disconnectedness,

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:45.300
a little bit, right?

00:08:45.420 --> 00:08:48.040
so that Python can have its changes

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:50.360
without you constantly chasing it, right?

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:51.400
Yeah, exactly.

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:54.880
So yeah, kind of what we kind of came up with

00:08:55.080 --> 00:09:01.140
was we would do the integration at the C level using Python C

00:09:01.260 --> 00:09:04.920
API as a way of consuming Python through sort of like

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:05.940
an embedded mode.

00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:09.620
Not many projects do this, but it is definitely possible.

00:09:09.780 --> 00:09:12.419
So you can spin up a Python interpreter

00:09:12.440 --> 00:09:16.140
inside another process, which in our case is the net process.

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:18.260
Yeah, and I think Blender does that.

00:09:19.180 --> 00:09:23.740
I'm pretty sure that there's a bunch in the film and movie industry

00:09:24.060 --> 00:09:25.960
that do that for their automation pipelines.

00:09:27.540 --> 00:09:28.820
I don't think it's that great.

00:09:30.660 --> 00:09:36.160
I talked to some of the people from the movie and video space,

00:09:38.420 --> 00:09:40.640
and most of them are still running on Python, too,

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:42.660
because when they wrote the implementation

00:09:42.880 --> 00:09:45.300
to integrate the thing, integrate CPython,

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:47.020
they're like, well, it's done.

00:09:47.280 --> 00:09:49.860
And like you kind of said, Python moved on.

00:09:50.020 --> 00:09:51.100
And they're like, well, that's a lot of work.

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:53.560
And then we got to-- we'll just leave it on Python 2.

00:09:53.620 --> 00:09:54.700
And that's not great.

00:09:55.920 --> 00:09:56.740
Yeah, exactly.

00:09:56.980 --> 00:09:59.220
So we looked at this and said, we want to be--

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:00.940
we want to support the newest version of Python.

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:05.340
We want to support the sort of practically old version,

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:08.500
which I think you settled around 3.8,

00:10:08.620 --> 00:10:11.500
was like as old as I was willing to go.

00:10:11.580 --> 00:10:14.480
And I think we maybe pushed that forward to 3.9

00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:16.340
because there were some specific features we need.

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:20.100
And on the.NET side,

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:23.600
again, there's a lot of changes happening in.NET.

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:25.520
Sharon, maybe you can share a bit more,

00:10:25.680 --> 00:10:29.560
but like, you know,.NET's going through just as many changes.

00:10:29.780 --> 00:10:33.400
So we've got like two moving, constantly moving platforms

00:10:34.200 --> 00:10:36.440
and we want to make an integration between the two of them.

00:10:36.680 --> 00:10:39.720
So let's think about how can we do this in a way which is

00:10:39.720 --> 00:10:40.560
actually maintainable.

00:10:42.020 --> 00:10:45.560
And we can test it, and we can make it stable as well.

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:48.880
Yeah, one thing maybe you could speak to as part of this.

00:10:51.040 --> 00:10:55.160
People might know.NET as this Windows programming library

00:10:56.020 --> 00:10:57.560
that you use Visual Studio with.

00:10:59.060 --> 00:11:01.280
But it's changed a lot since then.

00:11:01.820 --> 00:11:02.760
There's.NET Core.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:03.620
There's open source.

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:04.420
It runs on Linux.

00:11:04.680 --> 00:11:07.820
there's a lot of different things that have been changed about it, right?

00:11:08.540 --> 00:11:11.800
Yeah, and it's a fairly common misconception that we've got is that

00:11:12.420 --> 00:11:13.620
people equate.NET with Windows.

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:15.820
And historically, that's true.

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:19.160
That's where I got started is developing on Windows.

00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:21.920
And I'll be honest, I'm still a Windows developer.

00:11:22.400 --> 00:11:24.880
It's what my primary OS has been.

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:28.840
I've flirted with macOS and Linux over the years,

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.460
but Windows is just where I'm more comfortable with.

00:11:32.160 --> 00:11:36.400
But I think it's been a bit over a decade now

00:11:37.420 --> 00:11:40.700
since they essentially relaunched.NET.

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:42.900
It was originally called.NET Core.

00:11:43.940 --> 00:11:46.140
So now we kind of have these two streams concurrently.

00:11:46.220 --> 00:11:47.340
You've got.NET Framework,

00:11:47.420 --> 00:11:52.180
which is the one that is what we traditionally thought of as.NET.

00:11:52.280 --> 00:11:55.320
It ships kind of with Windows and stuff like that.

00:11:55.320 --> 00:12:02.120
So it's very much designed around that longer tail support lifecycle

00:12:02.140 --> 00:12:07.200
and whatnot it is fairly stable but also getting minimalistic investment just because

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:17.980
it has that kind of need to be stable and consistent um year in year out so then we have .NET core or

00:12:20.420 --> 00:12:26.440
now now we just kind of refer to it as .NET just naming things is hard let's let's be honest um

00:12:27.180 --> 00:12:30.820
So we have.NET and every year a new release comes out

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:33.720
and this is like a major framework,

00:12:34.650 --> 00:12:36.160
like a major revision to the runtime.

00:12:36.940 --> 00:12:39.700
So.NET 9 is actually coming out next week,

00:12:39.920 --> 00:12:42.380
at least at the time of recording, it's next week.

00:12:43.100 --> 00:12:46.000
And this is considered like a short-term support lifecycle.

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:48.600
So if you're familiar with support life cycles

00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:51.260
of a lot of runtimes out there now,

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:53.920
so like Node popularized this quite a lot now.

00:12:54.800 --> 00:12:56.420
Python is starting to adopt it a bit more

00:12:56.440 --> 00:13:01.320
that kind of you have this yearly rolling life cycle and um and you'll have long-term supports

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:07.120
and short-term support so the long term is every even number so .NET eight being the most recent

00:13:07.500 --> 00:13:12.320
long-term support um uh .NET six was the previous one which is actually going out of support

00:13:13.210 --> 00:13:17.880
uh next week and time of recording uh and then we'll so we'll have .NET eight and .NET nine

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:22.580
and to anthony's point then you've got two versions of .NET that we're trying to target

00:13:25.060 --> 00:13:34.140
So we originally, very early on, it was just going to result in too many variants in terms

00:13:34.310 --> 00:13:43.020
of.9 is about to land here, bringing more features that we want to adopt.

00:13:43.360 --> 00:13:48.180
So we need to start looking at all the other things inside of.9, we want to make it playable.

00:13:49.320 --> 00:13:54.680
So hopefully those of you listening can understand something

00:13:54.860 --> 00:14:00.460
like digitalization in what was working out where we land

00:14:00.560 --> 00:14:01.840
from versioning standpoints.

00:14:02.480 --> 00:14:04.780
But also being realistic of where people are

00:14:04.940 --> 00:14:05.880
and developing their applications.

00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:10.600
We couldn't just target Python 3.13 and.NET 9

00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:13.440
as the only supportive versions because, to be honest,

00:14:13.560 --> 00:14:15.140
that's not where most packages are.

00:14:15.260 --> 00:14:17.320
That's not where most projects are going to be.

00:14:18.020 --> 00:14:20.260
So we have to make some calls there.

00:14:20.620 --> 00:14:24.620
Yeah, you do have to have a little bit of slack in there.

00:14:25.270 --> 00:14:27.820
Even for me and some of my web apps and stuff,

00:14:27.910 --> 00:14:29.700
I had to wait a few weeks to upgrade to 3.13

00:14:31.020 --> 00:14:33.460
because some dependency of a dependency

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:36.140
had something that had been removed,

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:38.680
been deprecated for a while and was removed

00:14:38.710 --> 00:14:39.240
and it didn't work.

00:14:39.360 --> 00:14:41.680
Well, try that again in a few weeks and see how it works.

00:14:41.860 --> 00:14:43.660
Eventually they caught up.

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:46.560
But yeah, it's definitely a challenge.

00:14:48.140 --> 00:14:54.320
All right, Anthony, when we opened this, you mentioned there had been other attempts, other ways.

00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:59.020
The one that comes to mind for me is IronPython, right?

00:14:59.960 --> 00:15:08.560
IronPython is a CLR implementation of Python, and that's a pretty big difference right there than what you're trying.

00:15:08.860 --> 00:15:12.640
So maybe contrast it with some of the things that people have done previously.

00:15:14.160 --> 00:15:23.880
Yes, there's probably three projects I think that have been done previously that kind of sit in the same space, but they have different goals.

